        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>681 Lexington Ave<lb/>
                NEW YORK.<lb/>
                21 Mch&#47;82<lb/>
                11 P. M.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have just read<lb/> Mme Ragozin&#39;s anti&#45;Jewish article<lb/> in the Century &#40;Scribner&#39;s&#41; for April.<lb/>  Miss Lazarus is to reply next month<lb/> but with all regard for Miss L.<lb/> I do not think that&#44; even if she<lb/> has the ability&#44; &#40;which I question&#41;<lb/> she <del></del> has&#93; is sufficient authority.<lb/>  The article is the most danger&#45;<lb/>ous that has yet appeared&#8212;far<lb/> more so than any Goldwin<lb/> Smith&#39;s and the rejoinder must<lb/> needs<sic></sic> come from the very highest<lb/> authority.  Will not you undertake<lb/> the task&#63;  I know how much<lb/> your time is occupied&#59; I know how<lb/> reluctant you are to appear in the<lb/> public prints but I know too that<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>never has duty been more urgent.<lb/>  I wish to God&#44; that I myself could<lb/> undertake the vindication of His<lb/> people.  You can will you&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Excuse my writing to you in this<lb/> almost arbitrary strain but I feel<lb/> that we are resting under imputa<lb/>tions which if not dispelled will<lb/> react&#44; and rightly&#44; upon all Israel&#44;<lb/> and I look to you as the leader<lb/> whom I trust and love&#44; to champion<lb/> our cause.<lb/></p>
            <p>Ever faithfully yours<lb/>
                Cyrus L. Sulzberger<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S Morais<lb/>
                Philada.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
